<SubSection title="Allowable Strength Design">

<strong>Design Requirement:</strong> A structural design is intended to support and/or transmit loads while maintaining safety and utility: <strong><em>don't break</em></strong>. Strength of a structure reflects its ability to resist failure.

<Itemize>
    <Item> <strong>Ultimate load ( <InlineEquation equation="P_u" /> ):</strong> force when specimen fails (breaks).</Item> 
    <Item> <strong>Ultimate normal stress ( <InlineEquation equation="\\sigma_u" /> ):</strong> <DisplayEquation equation="\\sigma_u = \\frac{P_u}{A}\\" /></Item>
</Itemize>

 A structure is safe if its strength exceeds the required strength.

 <strong>Factor of Safety (FS):</strong> Ratio of structural strength to maximum (allowed) applied load (<InlineEquation equation="P_{all}" />).

<DisplayEquation equation="P_{all} \\le \\frac{P_u}{FS}\\" />

 Similarly, <DisplayEquation equation="\\sigma_{all} \\le \\frac{\\sigma_u}{FS}\\" />

</SubSection>

